 they proved superfluous: no cryingcame from the nursery to interfere with my work--Dr. Olga Repnin, the storyof an invented Russian professor in America, which was to be published(after a bothersome spell of serialization entailing endless proofreading)by Lodge in 1946, the year Annette left me, and acclaimed as "a blend ofhumor and humanism" by alliteration-prone reviewers, comfortably unaware ofwhat I was to prepare some fifteen years later for their horrifieddelectation.

